results.name: Number of ways of writing n as a sum of seven nonnegative cubes.
comment: Order matters. This is the coefficient of q^n in the expansion of {Sum_{m>=0} q^(m^3)}^7.
It is known that a(n)>0 if n is even and > 454.
link: Seiichi Manyama, Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..10000
N. D. Elkies, Every even number greater than 454 is the sum of seven cubes, arXiv:1009.3983
xref: Sums of k cubes, number of ways of writing n as, for k=1..9: A010057, A173677, A051343, A173678, A173679, A173680, A173676, A173681, A173682.
